    <name>Your Mathematics Journey</name>
    <intro>&lt;h3&gt;Reflections on Mathematics Teaching and Learning&lt;/h3&gt;
&lt;p dir="ltr" style="text-align: left;"&gt;Adult learners of mathematics have all had prior experiences as math students—some hopefully positive, some challenging and problematic—in a variety of mathematics classrooms. Having opportunities in their math classes to reflect on those learning experiences
    is an important way for your students to begin to re-envision what mathematics could be for themselves as math learners. It is also an important way for teachers to get to know their students and sets the foundation for later activities that engage
    learners in new ways of doing and learning mathematics. In ANI&amp;nbsp;2.0, we’ll begin with this activity as well to both model the activity and get to know each other as doers and learners (and teachers) of mathematics.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;h4 style="padding-top: 20px"&gt;Assignment&lt;/h4&gt;
&lt;p dir="ltr" style="text-align: left;"&gt;In this activity, you will share your experience with mathematics both as a learner and a teacher. You can write a brief memo, make a video, create a slideshow, or share in whatever medium you like.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p dir="ltr" style="text-align: left;"&gt;You should address some of your early experiences as well as later experiences, including&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;ul&gt;
    &lt;li&gt;Experiences with teachers (in any grade), both positive and negative&lt;/li&gt;
    &lt;li&gt;How your attitude towards mathematics has changed over the years (if it has)&lt;/li&gt;
    &lt;li&gt;Why you like or don’t like math&lt;/li&gt;
    &lt;li&gt;What feels good about doing math or learning math or teaching math&lt;/li&gt;
    &lt;li&gt;What is exciting or scary for you in learning or teaching math&lt;/li&gt;
    &lt;li&gt;Whatever else you’d like to share&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;
&lt;p dir="ltr" style="text-align: left;"&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Instructions for submitting the assignment:&lt;/strong&gt; Click the ADD SUBMISSION button below. You may then type your response in the text box or upload a file. Click SAVE CHANGES to save your work. You may continue to edit your response as needed.&amp;nbsp;&lt;strong&gt;Click SUBMIT ASSIGNMENT when you are done.&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;</intro>
